## PRD — Authentication, User Model & Backend Foundation (Supabase)

**Priority:** 🔴 High  
**Status:** Foundational (must be implemented before dynamic portal features)

This PRD defines how users authenticate, how identities and organizations are modeled, and how backend data is structured so the Superwork portal moves from a static mockup to a real, multi-tenant HubSpot consulting platform.

---

## 1. Purpose & Scope

**Purpose**  
Enable real users, real organizations, real permissions, and real data in the Superwork customer portal.

Without this PRD:
- The portal is only a visual mockup
- No customer data is trustworthy
- Projects, billing, communication, and assets cannot function

This PRD intentionally combines **authentication, user model, organization model, and core backend schema**, because these are inseparable in a multi-organization consulting platform.

---

## 2. User Types (Non-Negotiable)

The platform supports **three user types**, each with distinct access patterns.

### 2.1 Customer
- Belongs to **one customer organization**
- Can invite colleagues into the same organization
- Can:
  - View subscription, balance, usage, and invoices
  - View and comment on projects
  - Access delivered assets
- Cannot:
  - See other customer organizations
  - Access internal SOPs or admin tools

### 2.2 Provider (Consultant / CSM / Account Manager)
- Belongs to **Superwork**
- Can be assigned to **multiple customer organizations**
- Can:
  - Manage and update projects
  - Communicate with customers
  - Upload deliverables
- Cannot:
  - Access platform-wide admin configuration
  - Modify customer billing unless explicitly allowed

### 2.3 Admin
- Belongs to **Superwork**
- Full platform access
- Can:
  - Create and manage customer organizations
  - Add customer and provider users
  - Override access and data
  - Manage platform-level configuration

---

## 3. Authentication (Supabase Auth)

### 3.1 Authentication Method
- Supabase Auth
- Email + password login
- Password reset via email
- Session-based authentication (JWT handled by Supabase)

### 3.2 Session Management Requirements
- Persistent sessions across browser refresh
- Automatic token refresh
- Server-side session access for protected routes
- Secure logout

**Acceptance criteria**
- Users are not logged out unexpectedly
- Invalid sessions immediately revoke access
- Session state is available both client- and server-side

---

## 4. Signup & Onboarding Flows

### 4.1 Self-Service Customer Signup (Public Website)

**Primary path for product-led growth**

**Flow**
1. User signs up via the Superwork website
2. Supabase Auth creates the user
3. A **new customer organization** is automatically created
4. The user becomes:
   - `user_type = customer`
   - `organization_role = admin`
5. User is redirected to portal onboarding

**Rules**
- One organization per self-service signup
- No automatic provider assignment
- Default plan state: trial / inactive (defined in billing PRD)

---

### 4.2 Admin-Created Customer Account

**Used for sales-led or enterprise onboarding**

**Flow**
1. Admin creates organization
2. Admin invites initial customer user
3. User completes signup via invite
4. User lands directly in the portal

---

### 4.3 Customer Invites (Colleagues)

**Used after organization exists**

**Flow**
1. Customer admin invites colleague
2. Invite link creates user inside same organization
3. Role assigned at invite (`admin`, `member`, `viewer`)

**Rules**
- Only customer admins can invite
- Invites never create new organizations

---

### 4.4 Provider Signup

- Admin-only
- Providers cannot self-register
- Providers may belong to multiple customer organizations

---

### 4.5 Admin Signup

- No public admin signup
- Seeded manually or via internal tooling

---

## 5. Protected Routes & Access Control

### Principles
- Never trust client-side role checks
- Enforce permissions server-side
- Scope all data by organization membership

### Conceptual Route Groups
- `/portal/*` → authenticated users
- `/portal/customer/*` → customers + providers (scoped)
- `/portal/internal/*` → providers + admins
- `/portal/admin/*` → admins only

**Acceptance criteria**
- Customers cannot access internal or admin routes
- Providers cannot access admin routes
- Users can only access organizations they belong to

---

## 6. Core Data Model (Supabase Database)

### 6.1 Organizations (Companies)

Represents a **customer company** or **Superwork** itself.

**Fields**
- `id` (UUID, PK)
- `name`
- `type` (`customer` | `superwork`)
- `domain` (e.g. `company.com`)
- `website_url` (e.g. `https://company.com`)
- `country` (ISO-2 or ISO-3, e.g. `NO`, `SE`, `US`)
- `created_at`

**Intent**
- Root entity for billing, projects, access control
- Enables future domain verification and enrichment

---

### 6.2 Users

Represents an authenticated person.

**Fields**
- `id` (matches Supabase auth user id)
- `email`
- `name`
- `user_type` (`customer` | `provider` | `admin`)
- `created_at`
- `last_login_at`

Auth credentials live in Supabase Auth; profile data lives here.

---

### 6.3 Organization Memberships (Critical)

Enables:
- Customers inviting colleagues
- Providers working across multiple customers

**Fields**
- `id`
- `user_id`
- `organization_id`
- `role` (`admin` | `member` | `viewer`)
- `created_at`

This table defines **tenant boundaries**.

---

### 6.4 Projects

Represents consulting work.

**Fields**
- `id`
- `organization_id`
- `title`
- `status` (`planned` | `in_progress` | `blocked` | `completed`)
- `progress_percentage`
- `created_at`
- `updated_at`

---

### 6.5 Project Assignments

Maps providers to projects.

**Fields**
- `id`
- `project_id`
- `user_id` (provider)
- `role` (`lead` | `contributor`)
- `created_at`

---

### 6.6 Messages / Conversations

Contextual communication tied to projects.

**Fields**
- `id`
- `project_id`
- `author_user_id`
- `message_body`
- `is_internal` (boolean)
- `created_at`

Internal messages are never visible to customers.

---

### 6.7 Assets (Metadata)

Files stored in Supabase Storage.

**Fields**
- `id`
- `project_id`
- `uploaded_by_user_id`
- `file_name`
- `file_type`
- `storage_path`
- `is_final`
- `created_at`

---

### 6.8 Invoices

Read-only in the portal.

**Fields**
- `id`
- `organization_id`
- `invoice_number`
- `amount`
- `currency`
- `status` (`paid` | `due`)
- `issued_at`
- `due_at`
- `pdf_url`

---

## 7. Backend API Requirements

### Characteristics
- Server-side only
- Uses Supabase client
- Protected by Row-Level Security (RLS)

### Required Capabilities
- Fetch authenticated user + memberships
- Fetch organizations user belongs to
- Fetch projects scoped by organization
- Fetch messages (respecting `is_internal`)
- Upload and list assets
- Fetch invoices
- Invite users to organizations

---

## 8. Row-Level Security (RLS) — Mandatory

### Core Rules
- Customers: access only their organization
- Providers: access assigned organizations/projects
- Admins: access everything

**Acceptance criteria**
- No cross-org data leakage
- Direct table access is safe
- All tables have RLS enabled before production

---

## 9. Explicit Non-Goals (v1)

- No anonymous access
- No public provider signup
- No automatic domain verification
- No automatic org merging
- No cross-organization collaboration

---

## 10. Key Acceptance Criteria (Summary)

- Users can self-signup and log in
- Organizations are created and isolated correctly
- Customers can invite colleagues safely
- Providers can work across multiple customers
- Admins have full oversight
- No feature depends on hardcoded data

---

## 11. Definition of Done

When this PRD is complete:
- The portal supports real customers and consultants
- All data is multi-tenant and secure
- Future PRDs can assume authenticated, organization-scoped reality
- The product is no longer a mockup, but a real platform
